text:
SONS & DAUGHTERS OF WW - III
 Our sons and daughters serve in harm‚Äôs way
 To defend our way of life.
 Some are students, some grandparents
 Many a husband or wife.

They face great odds without complaint
 Gambling life and limb for little pay.
 So far away from all they love
 Fight our soldiers for whom we pray.

The plotters and planners of America‚Äôs doom
 Pledge to murder and maim all they can.
 From early childhood they are taught
 To kill is to become a man.

They exploit their young as weapons of choice
 Teaching in Heaven virgins will await.
 Destroying lives along with their own
 To learn of their falsehoods too late.

The fearful cry we must submit
 And find a way to soothe them.
 Where defenders worry if we stand down
 The future for America is grim.

Now‚Äôs not the time to fight one another
 Or kiss our enemy‚Äôs cheek.
 All through history it remains the same
 The strong enslave the weak.

May God continue to bless America
 Refusing evil the upper hand.
 It‚Äôs up to us to stay resolute
 Defending the liberty of Man.

text: My father was an Officer in the Army, my mother met him when I was 7 years old. He was an amazing man that was nurturing and always made me feel safe. He always spoke to me about how our country received him when he returned from Vietnam. His medals he never hung. His stories he rarely told. He was made to feel he was bad even though he was following orders. Still yet, he instilled in me a love for my country. He loved this country. God has been pressing something on my heart to the point I have been in tears, Could we please receive our service members better than they have been received in the past?? They need us right now. They need God or need us to stand in belief for them. They have seen things we could not see. They have seen things we could never stomach. We need to be ready to catch them up and support them. Also, they have been extracting survivors of things again we could not stomach. We need to be able to catch them as well. Mostly just listen to them and Believe. How can we not? We cannot lose them after all that has occurred. Thank you for reading my request. Let's stand together in prayer for them in whatever they need to be able to recover. Praying a hedge of protection around them now. Amen.

text: Listen kid, although your passion is appreciated, please speak with some of our older veterans who have been through true hell. Listen to their stories and know what you are getting yourself into. Joining the military is not just a simple choice, it is a thing that changes you and how you live for the rest of your life. It's a lifestyle, not just something you take lightly. I'm not telling you not to join, but I urge you to know what you are getting into. Visit The Wall a few times for Memorial Day, feel those cries on the other side, look into the eyes of men who left their souls on the battlefield, and know that that could be you someday.

text:
Wayne, I need you to do something.  I want to go somewhere quiet.  I want you to close your eyes and listen.  I don't want you to listen to what's around you, I want you to listen to your soul. Can you hear it?  Can you hear that thing inside you that calls you to serve?  Can you hear that thing inside that tells you no matter what comes at you to not give up the fight?  Do you hear that thing inside of you that tells you not to give up on your brothers?  If you don't hear those things don't sign up.  If you do, like I did several years ago,  I'll be honored to call you a brother no matter what branch you choose to go in to.

Signed,
A US Army vet

text:
¬†@No no¬† Physically I'm back since almost 20 years, but what I've seen and also done will be in my mind until that day my breath will stop.

In Germany there's a saying... The people will remember God and the Military at the days they need them, but if the danger is gone they will forget and reject God and the soldiers.

It's even legal for the people in Germany to say that soldiers are potentially murderers.

But no one, except those who have to do it, will never know how it is to pull the trigger.

It's final, and it's not reverseable.

And those feelings will never ever leave your soul.
author: Konrad Baresa

text:
¬†@Konrad Baresa¬† Sir, it is for Our Families and Country that We make these sacrifices. And Yes, it never leaves us.
Pay no attention to the nasties and Nay Sayers. There are always those who will enjoy the fruits of what we had to do, nor the personal price we paid.
When I returned, in 1971, we were called "Baby Killers". Did this hurt? Yes, until we considered the source.
Ignore the foolish ones. There are always some with their heads in the sand. But always remember, we are the ones who protect their asses!!

text:
My advice is understand fully what it is you're signing up for. Don't just go in for the romanticized bullshit movies and recruiters feed you. Understand you will hurt, you will fear, and you will cry. Once you get that well into your head and still wish to carry on, once you understand what exactly it is you're sacrificing, then enlist. Don't do it for some dumb shit like college or a job. Think about the shit you don't want to think about then realize there is a very good chance that that may become your new reality.

By all means enlist and serve. Just please understand what you're giving up and who you're giving it up for.

text: ¬†@firefox5926¬† You act as if being a solider is inherently evil. Evil will always exist and Evil will always present a threat. The reason the US is so feared is because of our soldiers. The best defense is a great offense. The past 2 times America was attacked, we have overwhelmingly defeated our adversaries. Pearl Harbor lead to the Atomic Bomb, 9/11 lead to a complete and total take over of an entire country in 30 days, most of which was done within a few days.  We stayed to find the fuckhead who did 9/11. We killed him. Now we are there to help aid the people to fight for themselves. Everybody deserves freedom, but freedom is not free. You need to understand that. Why do you think Americans own so many guns? We had to fight for everything to gain our freedom. We know what it costs. text: I've lost many of my brothers, I've watched them take their last breath, but when you're there in that moment you are almost numb to it, the hardest part is coming home and having to remember, when things slow down and you have time to think. It's hard to deal with all the loss, sad part is I've lost more of my brothers state side than over seas. The war isn't over when we come back , at that point the physical fighting is over and that inner battle begins. Having to kill and living in the constant fear of being killed gets to you, you never feel "normal " again.  If you have someone in your life that's seen battle, be there for them, even if its 5 minutes of talking a day, sometimes it's that 5 minute phone call at that right moment that makes someone feel less alone.  GOD BLESS!  OORAH & SEMPER FI

text: I'm using my son's account. My dad never made it home. I can never ever hug him again.. Every time I hear the pledge of allegiance or sing an anthem or see a picture of him no matter how many years have gone by do I not think about him. Even though I was 4 when he died not a time goes by that I don't remember the steps I took going to his funeral in the mountains and the things I saw and heard are as clear today as they were back in the 60's. When people die it is not just them that dies...it's their wife, kids, parents tears never dry up hurt never goes away.  Please let my dad rest on your shoulders and let him help to keep you strong so that you will never do anything to yourself to not be there for others. Because you will always be a soldier that is still there to help your kid and other kids and the people your kids can help because you made it. STAY STRONG AND BRAVE DEAR SOLDIER. I'm glad you got to stay.

As I served my father "borrowed" me something I had to bring him back personally. So keeping the light on until the soldier is back is also a great tradition.


I think it doesn't matter what tradition you establish to show your soldiers you want them back healthy. but do such.


The politics should do it (also here in Germany), and also the Family should establish their private and own traditions.


As a mother of a daughter who missed so much of the life of my daughter I know how important it is, to know there is someone who would awaits you and miss you.


no politician of that world could motivate the soldiers more than a soft: "please come back mom" from a child you dearly love. or a teddy bear from that child or your own parents.


But I not only know how it is to leave a child for a deployment, I also know how it is to wait for a dad to come back.

text:
¬†@Steven Neeley¬† No, we did not.  What gives one the right to interfere with other countries political and religious policies?  It is not up to any country to try to solve the problems of the world by war.  If the ways of others disturb us, then we should apprehend the leadership of that source of disturbance, not kill off huge numbers of the population that in and of itself has no control of their leadership.  The point is it is the leadership that is corrupt, not necessarily the population.  Why kill off people who are not directly involved in ruffling our feathers?  Do we now have enough conceit that we think it tolerable to govern what religions, customs, and rights, even control, others should have?  It seems it is always religious differences combined with natural resource coveting, that  governments display their arrogance.  You cannot blame the whole population for the transgressions of their leadership.  
If you think that we engage in war for the protection of freedom, how many missions have you been deployed to in Uganda, to combat the genocide, or any other 3 world country for the same reason?  I'll safely bet your answer would be none.,  But on the other hand,  how many deployments have you been on to protect resources that we are trying to control or gain in the middle east?  My friend, it is all about the money.  Thats why war is such a waste.  Trying to control the worlds resources seems to be the objective of most (if not all) wars.  Although war spurs the economy by providing jobs to those who manufacture weapons, and those who sell them, and those who support troops by whatever means, it is not practical in the long run when one counts the dead.  We now fill our gas tanks with the blood of those who tried to defend that resource from us.  I now refuse to have a car, or use public transportation because of that fact. 
  I am also a Viet Nam vet, so it is not like I haven't a clue about the military.  30 years and retired in the late 80's.  I had your viewpoint for a while until I realised the truth snd motivation behind it all.  So, you believe what they tell you, and you have the right to do so, but I will no longer believe the lies behind the propaganda and smoke screen  reasons for warfare.

text: Have you prepare for the mindset once you get out of the service? If you get far enough where you have to be deployed, and be in wars.  Once you get out how would you be able to handle your flashbacks,PTSD,reliving your night terrors, or seeing the ones you love that you are close getting killed in the line of duty? That you will be blaming yourself. As a veteran's wife, I have to tell my veteran that it is ok to cry, that it is ok to show your emotions, which in the service they train you not to show your emotions, that it isn't ok to cry. That it isn't his fault that he saw his Sargent's death, and he blames himself that it should've been him, and not his Sargent's. Unfortunately my husband isn't able to go to the VA, because another veteran has stolen my husband's benefit's. My veteran and I are currently homeless. He was promised all kinds of things, which has turn out to be a lie. He doesn't sleep days on out, and if anyone comes up behind him, he will be thrown into a major flashbacks. I have to tell him that it is ok to cry, that it is ok to feel like a human being, and that it wasn't his fault. That all his guilt should not be his, but only by our government. Why? Because he was following orders. This is what they don't want to tell you.

text: I for one, am immensely grateful for your service and please accept my apology for the way you all were treated. I was drafted but due to a family doctor who was against the war, I was listed as unable to serve due to a non- existent heart condition he reported to the local authorities. I found out later he pulled the same stunt with several other young men in our hometown. I did not find out he lied until a complete physical about 10 years later.  I dson't know if he was ever caught and punished. I certainly hope so.  I had planned on enlisting in the Navy specializing in avionics. Not being able to serve as my grand dad and my dad has left an empty spot in my heart .

text:
Hier ist der ganze text zum lied.


You missed my first step,
My first words, Dad.
This house is filled with pictures of someone I never had.
I know I've known your voice.
I think I know your smile.
Mommy says your clothes haven't smelled like your clothes in awhile.
I know I've read all your letters that say how you're doin' it for me.
And Mommy says how you're keepin' us safe even though it might not be easy to see.
We'll leave the light on until Daddy comes home.
We'll leave the light on for our soldier.
To remember all the fallen, fought, and all of those who served.
The soldiers that were beaten, and forever burn.
We'll leave the light on!
Late at night, when Mommy thinks she's all alone
I hear pray to God
"Lord, I don't know how much longer I can hold us together.
Alone, it's becoming so hard."
I know I've read all your letters that say how you do it for me.
And Mommy says how you're keepin' us safe
Even though it might not be easy to see.
Mommy, we'll leave the light on until Daddy comes home.
We'll leave the light on for our soldier.
To remember all the fallen, fought, and those who served.
Soldiers that were beaten and forever burn.
We'll leave the light on.
...
We'll leave the light on until Daddy comes home.
We'll leave the light on for our soldier.
To remember all the fallen, all those who served.
The soldiers that feel it and forever burn.
Let's leave the light on.

text:
I would re-evaluate their reasoning for doing so.


You say they gave so much for us and what we do, could you be a little more specific?  Don't soldiers just follow the orders they are given, doesn't matter what country or theatre of operations they are in.  You are not given the reason for your service, you are just told it is for the protection of your freedom. How do you think our freedom was threatened by the war in Viet Nam?  Now that we are out of there, their country has prospered and is even now a tourist attraction.  Was that what we were fighting for there?   To keep that from happening, as we are not profiteering from the result?  Do you even know what that war was about?  You may call the dislikes a disgrace, I call it being rational.  You need to get the big picture, and quit believing everything you are fed by your government.  They are mostly liars and pompous politicians who vote on their own pay raises while watching sons, fathers sisters, mothers, aunts, uncles, march off to do their bidding while they sit back and rake in all the money war generates.  They could give a crap about who does it as long as it isn't them.   It's Semper DIE, not Semper Fi...
author: Mr x

text:
¬†@Mr x¬† actually the Vietnam war was not initiated by the US. North Vietnam, a communist government declared war against south Vietnam a democratic republic. The US was in Vietnam to provide support to the South and ultimately lost the war. You're right soldiers do follow orders but if it were not for those soldiers following orders, there would be nothing in the way of another country declaring war  against us and winning. That country would likely impose on the freedoms we have today. Did you know that in most communist countries, you can be executed simply for speaking I'll of the government?
Sorry, I'll stand behind the United States military and government long before I'll put my life and liberty in the hands of a foreign communist nation.
author: Josiah M

text: ¬†@Josiah M¬† Yes Josiah, I understand your point of democracy.  That is not the issue here though.  What is the issue are the 47000 sons daughters husbands and wives that were killed because of religious differences in a country half a world away from our democracy.  Catholicism, vs.Confucianism. That was the issue and has been for thousands of years in that country.  How is it that our political leaders thought we have any business in the religious wars of other countries to start with?  How is that relevant to OUR democracy?  I say fix what we have here, and we do have our own problems democracy or not, before we go out and try to solve 30,000 year old problems in other countries.  When we are actually attacked by another country, and are put into the position of having to defend what is OURS, then I would be willing to fight, but not for some religious differences which are pure crap anyway.  We are not Romans, and should not be trying to manipulate the world to our points of view, or conquer more territories for our exploitation.  I say leave others to their tribal wars, stop providing weapons to others that eventually will be turned on us while in these countries. Most of all give the world its right to their own religious freedoms like you enjoy here. Or just be hypocritical, and feed the worlds manic war machine....
author: Mr x

text:
¬†@Mr x¬† I could see you point if it were true, but show me a war, the US was involved in simply for religious reasons. Far as I know, the US hasn't been involved in any kind of crusade. Even the Vietnam war was not based on religion, again, we were backing an ally. Our current war in the middle East is also not a war over religion. It's a war on terror. Remember 9-11. How about the 2015 Paris attacks? And now, terrorism is on our own soil where terrorists groups are using propaganda to indoctrinate US citizens. Don't tell me it doesn't happen. It does.

No. We absolutely should not be putting weapons in the hands of a potential enemy. We absolutely should be focusing on our country, and I think for the most part we are. With the national debt at an all time low, and unemployment the same way. Before the US can pull out of the middle East, it needs to become self sufficient. We rely on resources coming from that area. Terrorism and war in that area devastates our trade economy. So the US is using it's power to stabilize the region. It's not a war to force religion.

Further, while I don't think you implied this, others have implied that we should de-fund our military. That's a bad idea. That is our defense. Does anybody really believe that all the countries of the nuclear treaty destroyed and stopped producing nuclear weapons? Hell, Obama tried to give nuclear weapons to Iran. That would have been an absolute disaster. We need to be ready to defend at all times. Not just in times of war. We can't de-fund our military.

text:
It was nearly 30 years ago now. I didn't miss anything. Not really. Just the freedom to go and get a full English Breakfast and a cup of coffee. Back then though we didn't care about too much- it just wasn't healthy, except our unit, our company our regiment. That was the extent of our cares. Water, ammo, then food. In that order. 

Lovely tune by this young lady. If she was my daughter I'd be very proud that she actually cares.

Not many millennials do these days. My Dad used to fly Hunters in the RAF, back in the 60's. I guess it was this upbringing, but I didn't find military life hard, just an extension, like a home from home.

I get it now, it's not easy for kids to relate to this. My son Max just thinks it's like a computer game. I know he knows different, but I don't want him to join. I swore on my life to my ex-wife I'd never talk about it to him and I haven't. When he asks (and he has done many times) I have to shake it off and deflect. I just said I managed the parking.

Never would have happened when I was a kid. Had all my Dad's pilot friends over all the time. It was almost a given I was going in. They just wanted to know what regiment. I told them as a boy I never wanted to be a flyer.- Too much brain damage. They used to laugh. - (My Dad has since taught me to fly a light aircraft at RAF Akrotiri in Cyprus- that was really sweet)

Then that day arrives. I remember walking up to the gate and some corporal comes out and asks me what my excuse to live was? Welcome. Guards Depot, Pirbright. No coffee and 26 weeks of hate and discontent. - (saying that it wasn't so bad,) if you were fit and committed, the DS had you pegged in 2 days.I think in that time they had already decided who was going to pass and who was "mag-to-grid" (get rid). I loved it for the most part and always went above and beyond, they never had to beast me. - But they did anyway.

That first night in. 19 years old in a billet (Caterham company lines) with 20 other guys. Some of them are crying (never understood that) all of us though are quietly freaking out.

Think full metal jacket USMC. Guards Depot back then was like that. DS with their peaks right in your face screaming at you. Anything you did was wrong. The bad thing was it just went on and on and on. No let up. The only real time we had to ourselves was when we were running. 

From dawn till dusk. Running. Often in full kit, usually with the longest assault course in the Army at the end of it.. Any Guardsman will tell you.. the Seven Sisters- Sandhills, one after the other. Then the worst was NBC kit training. Shit, if things got that bad where we all have to wear this gear for weeks? Well. that's the job.

I look back the training seems to fly by- (it felt long and hard at the time). -That's what she said. Started with so many, just left with half at best at the end. 

It seems to me that the civilian world is somewhat fascinated by that transition we undergo from Civies to Combat soldiers.

Trust me on this one....You have to do it it warts and all, then still you're still a grunt. 

Then deployment.- That's when the fun starts.

text: My dad is a veteran now, and this song really reminded me when my mom and I and my older brothers were never sure dad would be coming home when he got sent off. I've been blessed that my father came back to us everytime during those 23 years of his service. I'm in tears, because I know there have been times I knew, really knew, that there was a chance dad wouldn't come home. Now, my older brother is a soldier for this country, whose beautiful kids and a wife wait with us whenever he's called away for him to safetly come home. Bless all those who served and those who waited for their soldiers to come home. Bless especially those whose soldiers didn't. Their service will not be forgotten. At least, not by me.

text: All due respect, regardless of if you agree or disagree with whatever war is being waged, this song was dedicated to the soldiers who felt duty-bound to fight in it. Often times, soldiers leave families and loved ones behind who suffer, but still hold down the fort because they love them and, even if they can't understand why, they offer their support regardless. This song is meant as an anthem to those families, and to make a comment about rival politics and opinions is not only short-sighted, but is also very rude and inappropriate. You have a right to your views, and that's something to be respected. But please try to recognize the struggle and message behind what is being portrayed here. Can we not put aside political differences, just for 5 minutes, and give a respectful nod to the families of deployed soldiers and recognize that they do struggle, even if you don't agree with or understand why?
author: logan owens

Know that we would hug you if we could, if it were possible to help you feel better.  The NFL protesters are thoughtless, cruel cowards when the real heroes are those like your husband, doing what needed to be done to keep us safe at night.  They do it for a small salary, while the NFL players average $2 million a year and far too many of them are selfish and ugly on the inside.  After 9/11 I cried every time watching TV as Lee Greenwood's song played during professional games.  These NFL clowns have no concept of what real patriotism means and how it has protected our country for over 200 years.  I am Boycotting the NFL, 5 weeks now.  God bless you and your family!

text: I truly appreciate and love this video. As a former 1st Lieutenant, Scout Sniper for the 1st Special Forces Group ( Airborne), Joint Base Lewis McChord Washington State. Home of the US Army I Corps, 75th Army Ranger Battalion and all combat units, the proudest in the United States Army. Special Forces lead the way. I give the most respect and love to all my current and former brothers and sisters in uniform, get rest all, Special Forces is watching over you all and we will proudly give it all and even our very last breath for you to get back on that Transpo home and to your loving families. As we get laid to rest after getting you to your parents, your husband or wife, your children and friends who love and care for you, we'll lay at rest in a military Garrison in heaven. May all the families of fallen soldiers take solitude in the fact that their loved one gave every last drop of honor and pride to protect every single citizen of our great and powerful United States of America. We will never loose or look past your memories and will in all the units that you're from, may they celebrate your life and your service to our country! I wasn't obviously filled with enough of the honor and pride also I wasn't granted the absolute ultimate privilege of giving every single ounce and breath in order to give all back home the freedom to work a Monday thru Friday 9 to 5, Saturday and Sunday with family and friends. Taking the kids to do sports or maybe dance class. If not for the Elite and small percentage of Special Forces Operatives like myself and my brothers and sisters, living and in heaven, we are the ones who actually want to grant every single person in our great Country and all we protect, it's a Special Forces Group Sniper like me that will give every single part of my physical being, including our very last breath to get you the safety to be a family and live in peace and freedom. I can only wish with every single fiber of my being that I could have given you my life so you wake up in the morning and spend the day living life as freedom grants to you. So please remember this if a single thing from my post. I am your armor, sheild and the one who selflessly lays, I live still to this very day believing in the Army Special Forces and all Elite military units, we protect from civilians to Soldiers, Airmen, Sailors and Marines day in and out. At any time I would have been the one to tell everyone else to get to safety, as I walked into the fire, ready to die in order to provide a stopping force between the enemy and all who they threaten in any way. I will take any fight, face any threat, walk anyone under my protection to safety even if taking wounds and even as I would have been dying and getting ready for my last breath, I will still straighten my uniform, load my weapon and walk into the fire so you may enjoy life. I love my country and I would and still would die to uphold your safety and security. So sleep in peace tonight and dream of Daisy fields and new born babies. Tonight my special forces brothers and sisters are watching over you and will do everything including giving our last breath to ensure that all peoples are free, safe and stay that way! I am truly still in my heart, mind, soul and spirit, A Special Forces Operator, a scout sniper, One shot, one kill!  1st Lieutenant J. Mac., 1st Special Forces Group Airborne, Joint Base Lewis McChord Washington State. Special Forces lead the way, all the way HOOAH!

text: It's not perfect but I hear they are making improvements.  My son, veteran of two stints over in Iraq, was diagnosed initially with an incurable cancer, then after tests they said it was curable.  It was a hard road for him, numerous VA hospital visits where family took turns driving him, losing his hair, more nausea than you can possibly imagine, and in the end he has been and continues to be in remission.  Resuming his passion for running.  My experience as a father, of the VA was pretty good, they seemed to care, although at times they were swamped with patients.  What I saw was caring professionals trying to help our servicemen.  Hopefully the VA improves a lot more.

text: I remember when I was a kid. I had been told that one of my family members have died in combat. I was confused and asked what death was. I learned through the years that war will only kill one side, but in the end there will be a sacrifice that we must learn to honor and thank. I am planning on being a medic in the Air Force, so I won't have to kill anybody. If I die helping people, not only will I feel happy, but I'll die in honor for the people who lived because of me. I will bring your fathers and mothers home soon. I am always reaching out to men who fight in wars just to hear their stories and tell them that it's what they had to do. Orders are orders and we must follow them for we are heroes of America and healers of the people who serve.

text: They fight so we don't have to, and I thank you brave men and women. I thank you so I can; go to work, my daughter can go to school, I can watch my little boy play baseball, so I can make a bad dinner, go see a silly movie, drink beers with my childhood friend, get a speeding ticket for running late, go on blind dates with women my sister set me up with, so my mom can watch those horrible house wives, so my dad can tinker around his shed, so my nephew can be who he is with being afraid, my niece can go to a church of her choice, so I can say I don't believe, so my neighbor can be red and my other a blue and neither one will shut the hell up about it, so I can sleep well at night and do it all over again or, not. I thank you, because of you I never have to worry or sacrifice. Hell I thank you because to be honest, I don't even have think about it. But I teach my children to respect you and to understand that you are the reason we are able to take so much for granted. So thank you, thank you so very very much.

Your dad feels for you and your family. I know it's kinda hard but there's no other choice. You are always in his heart and mind. He is where he's‚Äã at for you, me, and all of our country. author: William Ortiz

text:
William Ortiz 
~  Thank you,  but I remember  when I was a little girl and he had been home for a long time but worked on base but would not come home for days or month's.   I found out that he was a P.O.W. and that he had PTSD  from the Korean war.    He drank  very heavily  and wouldn't remember  what he did or said.    Some scary things happened at home and he decided to  make our life better and safer by leaving for good.    I felt as though he left a empty hole in our life.   And he left he had no way of getting help.   All I want was to erase all the bad memories all the bad things he went through.  Just to have the father, our daddy that my twin sister and missed out on getting to know who he really was.   Maybe in heaven I will get to know him one day.  He's been gone since 1992.   When you know your father heart is not what you see everyday but that sweet and loving man that you got a glimpse of just a couple of time's  it makes you long for just another day just to change all the pain from the war and family.     If this didn't make since I'm sorry.   It's  just something I have felt for him for a very long time.   One side of our family 6 were happier with out him but devastated without him.
author: Jennifer Vieira

text:
The video is in memory of SPC Justin Rollins. The active duty soldier that freely gave of his time, as the lead, for the tribute is SFC. Seriously wish our gift and attempt to honor, respect and give back (we donate all proceeds form iTunes) was not belittled with such political correctness.  
For the record this video is filled with flaws, so there is no need to comment further as herein I am coming clean.
However, it is with great sadness that I do so. Not sad for the flaws but for those who miss the point of this tribute 
as truly the heart and hard work combined with the love and respect we poured into the production was truly missed. This video has meant a great deal to so many, who choose to see the true meaning instead of the flaws from perfection. 

"Remember The Fallen and Honor all Who have Served". With all of my Respect to all of them. - Jay Preston
author: Rylee Preston

text: Every recording, every performance has flaws. We are human: our flaws make us unique, and the same is true of the works we create. Nitpicking someone's work based on those flaws, on that uniqueness, is only appropriate when one is proofreading or editing someone's work at the artist's request. Especially with a video such as this, made with love to honor those who sacrifice of themselves to defend those they love. You did an amazing job, Rylee. God bless you, your family and all those you made this video in honor of.

text:
I was in the Navy from 1965 - 1969. I served my first 2 years in the Mediterranean Sea and it wasn't a vacation. There were times when death seemed imminent and most of us weren't afraid. For some strange reason watching this video something dawned on me. I'm sure other veterans who fought went through the same thing. What dawned on me was the dying part was easy. It's the families, especially young families with children that's the real agonizing. Being left behind not knowing if a husband or father is coming home. I can't even begin to imagine that specter of fear always nearby. 

We like to think that we endured so bravely, especially when we survive. The real endurance and bravery are those we leave behind. I'm thankful that I didn't have a wife and children when I served. Being in the military, especially during war, it almost impossible to think of what our families are going through. We had to focus to much that there was no room for anything else. Our families experience the exact opposite. 

I would like to see people thank the families for their service, they deserve it much more than we do.

Thomas

text:
Ms. Preston.  Thank you for such a wonderful song - it hit a personal chord in so many ways.

My Dad lost his father during WW II, when he was 11.  He was never one to speak of his sorrow, but I know he suffered terribly growing up without his Dad.

When I listen to your song, I think of him; about what he and his Mother and sibs must have gone through during the war while my Grandfather was deployed, and then afterwards when they got the news.

I also think of my own family during my own deployments - being away from my wife and daughter during the recent wars took a terrible tole on both of them.  In some ways, families suffer more than those deployed.

My father (US Army) died recently and will be buried in Arlington National Cemetery, joining his father (USA), two uncles (USA, USCG), and brother (USMC) in that Hallowed Ground.  When I leave this earth, I (USN/USMC) hope to join them there too, as does my nephew (USMC).

Again, thank you for such a wonderful song.

text:
Mr. Madden sir,  There are no words that I can say that can take away the pain. But good sir , the pain you feel  is not unique. You are now part of the tragic family of those whose loved ones have made the ultimate sacrifice for the freedom and security of this nation. As Thomas Jefferson stated  "The tree of Liberty must be refreshed from time to time by the blood of patriots and tyrants." This American realizes that I do not live in freedom and safety for free. Better men than I, have paid for my ticket on the freedom train. May God give you comfort from your pain. I am not the brightest light bulb in the chandelier, but perhaps the reason for your son coming into this world was to save those thirty five people. If you had not had him, they would have died. We all have our rolls in this play of life, and God writes the script. We have the choice to sit it out or fulfill our roll. I leave you with a quote form an American patriot;

"Our founding fathers, here in  this country, brought about the only true revolution that has ever taken place in man's history. Every other evolution simply exchanged one set of rulers for another set of rulers. But only here did that little band of men so advanced beyond their time that the world has never seen their like since, evolve the idea that you and I have within ourselves the God-given right and ability to determine our own destiny. But freedom is never more than one generation away from extinction. We didn't pass it on to our children in the bloodstream. The only way they can inherit the freedom we have  known is if we fight for it, protect it, defend it and then hand it to them with the well thought lessons of how they must do the same. And if you and I don't do this, then you and I may well spend our sunset years telling our children and our children's children what it was once like in America when men were free."   Ronald Reagan 40th President of The United States

text:
After looking at all the different videos of the home comings and the surprise them videos I came across this video.  Awesome very beautiful.  One of the best ones I have seen and I have been watching these for the last 4 hours.  I just couldn't quit watching them.  So many have given the ultimate in sacrifice for their country.

My great grand father was in the Navy in WW II, My Day a Navy man was in the Korean war and I was Navy in the Viet Nam conflict back in 66/67.  My Uncle on Dad's side was Army as was my 2 Uncles on my Mothers side.  They all made it home in one piece with out any mental or physical problems.
My youngest Son was in the Army and had 3 tours back in 2006/07 in the Saudi, Iran, Iraq area.  we were blessed that He came home all in one piece to.  He was married to a beautiful Lady and they have 3 beautiful children 8,5, and 3 and I am going to visit them this coming Christmas and hug him and his wife and spoil my Grand babies while there.

text: I served until I retired through turbulent times in a world gone crazy and I could never share in the praise for the military that exists today.¬† I can say beyond the shadow of a doubt¬†that just knowing that someone cares is a powerful thing for that soldier serving on that far distant hostile shore.¬† I returned to nothing and no one and it hurt more than you know;¬†the scars and pain linger today, despite the medication.¬† Keep up this outstanding work of remembering the troops.¬† Shower them with the love and respect they deserve.¬†Let them know that what they do is not a thankless job. We once said that freedom has a price that the protected will never know.¬† Well, I do believe that someone, somewhere, has seen the tally and with this outstanding effort, is working diligently, to balance those books. ¬†Never forget, never surrender.

text: Rylee Preston My friend showed me this video and I basically balled my eyes out.  My father went into the Army and my brother went into the Marines.  My family got a call saying that both my dad and brother were killed. My brother got out alive but he was pinned by debris. He was able to come home but died on his way. I just want to thank you for the uplifting encouragement  that I get where I listen to this. We played your song at both of their funerals and everyone cried but for a good reason.  I will never forget them and I will always remember what they did for me in my life.  A big sincere to you and your family. Thanks.

text:
Thank you elkper99.¬† Just want to clear something up. Please know SPC Justin Rollins is not my father. My father did not die. My dad and I are family friends with the Rollins. I did not know Justin in a way I could accurately tell his story. 'Soldiers Light' was inspired by Justin's memory, dedicated to all our troops, veterans, and their families. This song was written because my heart hurts!!¬† It hurts for the loss of a HERO, the loss his family has suffered, and for the losses and sacrifices of all those to whom it is dedicated.
I know I have never experienced this first hand, but the thought of losing a family member, like my dad the most important person in the world to me,¬† scares me.
In that context, my heart hurts for all of them.
SPC Justin Rollins and so many like him gave their lives in the name of freedom, for America, for us. What relay touches my heart, my soul, is when I think about their sacrifice on a "much smaller scale". I think about how in a way, they, Justin, gave his life for me! They died for me!¬† If everyone did the same, maybe we would not allow the suffering of our veterans, our soldiers would get the support and when needed the help they deserve, and our fallen would be honored and never forgotten by "all those they fought to protect".¬†¬† 'Soldiers Light' is my way to Remember and Honor them.¬†¬† Rylee :) ¬†

I watched this video and felt connected to the music. I believe this is now my favorite military tribute. Keep up the good work. And supporting the good fight!
author: ALEX JONES

text:
Good job young lady! Thanks for keeping my brothers in your thoughts & song.

As soldiers we go where we are told to go and we do our duty to the best that we can. We do not pick the fight, we just fight it. Our leaders send us, our fellow countrymen allow it and our blood is shed and our lives are lost.
The loss of a loved ones life is a sorrowful thing. I salute my brothers lost lives and the wounded. I am also saddened for the great loss of non-combatants for I'm sure their loved ones miss them as well.
Maybe one day our leaders will fight their own battle or lead us into battle from the front to prove it to be a worthy fight or better yet give us a righteous fight with the intention of truly wining. Till that day us pawns will keep on fighting each other and sadness will fill the hearts of many on all sides.

For Christ, Christian Family and Christendom,
The CaptainÔªø

text:
Rylee Preston,¬†
I'm currently deployed in Afghanistan and have left my wife and four children at home. As the hospital chaplain at the busiest combat hospital in country, I've seen too many service members who were sent home to grieving families. I also know countless soldiers, sailors, airmen, and marines who sacrifice every day in order to serve. The pain of leaving your family behind is intense.

Your song brought tears to my eyes and the encouragement I needed tonight before I went to bed tonight. Thanks for using your gifts in this way. You've been a blessing to me!

I am so honored to be the niece of a Vietnam Veteran, to all of our brave Troops and their families and our brave Veterans and their families I just want to tell y'all from the bottom of my heart, "Thank You" for y'alls wonderful service to our country, y'alls service to our country is very much appreciated!! Oh and to our Troops who are still serving our country, I always leave my light on for y'all. Please stay safe and come home safe and soon. Your supporter and prayer warrior,

Kyndal.

I could see how sad my dad was when telling me the story and that made me sad. I said to him "what can we do to help?" We talked about maybe doing a tribute with my next new song and with that Idea Justin's story inspired me to write the song.¬†¬† "ALL" proceeds from ITunes sales/sales of the song are being donated. text:
great song as a OIF vet made me remember a lot of stuff I suppressed. I remember I poem I wrote for PTSD class ill share
Here i lie in my tent sleepless, hot, covered in sweat.
once again the AC broke again.
i hear the jets flying overhead.
explosions sounding in the distance.
i got 60 days left of this shit, FUCK! got extended again.
haven't seen home in 2 years alone, tired, stretched thin.
friends lost wonder how it could ...happen to them hell i got to get up and arm up again.
got to make my stand in the sand anxious, anticipating the fight ahead.
stock cocked and locked ready to rock.
shit here comes a truck not one of us, won't stop told to open up.
happened so fast the moment flew by in a flash.
looking up moving forward enemy's dead why didn't you stop you dumb son of a bitch.
its then I realize now and then killing isn't hard getting the blood off is.

text:
I had the honor of serving in the same unit as Justin Rollins, Andrew Perkins, Ryan Bell, Cory Kosters, Justin Estes, and Robert Stanley - all Killed in Action on March 5th, 2007. Joshua Boyd died March 15th from wounds he sustained in that same attack. They were some of the best paratroopers in our unit: Cco 2/505 Parachute Infantry Regiment, 3rd BCT, 82nd Airborne Division, out of Patrol Base Olson, Samarra, Iraq.

This song is beautiful and definitely a wonderful tribute for each of them, the other fine Paratroopers we lost on that deployment, and for combat veterans who've paid the ultimate sacrifice - and for each of their families!  Rest easy, Paratroopers.

author: Dustin Manger

text:
My relationship with my dad is one where we talk a lot about real life.
I pulled from a lot of stories he has shared with me, and when he comes home late, I always leave the light on until daddy comes home. When I would bring the lyrics to him to see what he thought, he would make suggestions, he just does not like to admit it. Then our Music producer Christian helps tweak until it becomes the final cut. I hope that with this explanation noting is lost, as in the end it is a beautiful song in memory of Justin. Justin's story inspired me¬†
when my dad was telling me Justin's story about the Ride For The Fallen, and I could see how sad he was telling me the story. This made me sad, and I wanted to help. Like may dad keeps saying, Justin, all our fallen, Not forgotten Happy Veterans Day.¬† Rylee.¬† And please know, I wrote the lyrics not the music. ¬†
